\section{Introduction}
The main goal of this work is to generalize the bag boundary condition proposed in~\cite{Chodos1974}
by introducing the derivatives of the wave function in the boundary condition for any Lorentzian manifold $M$. 
For this purpose, we introduce the following action
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{S} = \frac{1}{2}i\int_M \bar{\psi} \gamma^\mu \partial_\mu \psi - \partial_\mu \bar{\psi} \gamma^\mu \psi 
+ \frac{1}{2}\int_{\partial M} ic \bar{\psi} \gamma^\alpha \partial_\alpha (1 + i \gamma^\bot) \psi
- \bar{\psi} \psi
\end{equation}
for a certain constant $c$. 
$\gamma^\bot$ here represents the component perpendicular to $\partial M$ in the incoming direction. \\
Remark that there is a problem on the dimensionality because of the $\gamma$-matrices, as the generators of a Clifford Algebra does not always have representation space of the same dimension when we reduce its dimension by one. 
This motivates the choice of $M$ with dimension $2k+3$
When $c \rightarrow 0$, the boundary condition becomes the bag condition. 
Furthermore, we suppose that $\psi$ and $\partial_\mu \psi$ vanish at $\partial(\partial M)$. 
By variational method, we can derive the equations of motion in the bulk and on the boundary
\begin{equation}\label{wen-motion}
\begin{cases}
i \gamma^\mu \partial_\mu \psi = 0  \quad \textrm{in $M$}\\
i \gamma^\alpha \partial_\alpha (1 + i\gamma^\bot) \psi = c^{-1}(1 + i\gamma^{\bot}) \psi \quad \textrm{on $\partial M$}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
We define $\phi = \gamma^0 \psi$. 
\cref{wen-motion} can be written as 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
i \partial_0 \phi = i \gamma^0 \gamma^j \partial_j \phi   \quad \textrm{in $M$}\\
i \partial_0(1 - i\gamma^\bot) \phi = i \big(\gamma^0 \gamma^a \partial_a (1- i\gamma^\bot)\phi + c^{-1}\gamma^0 (1-i \gamma^{\bot})\phi \big)  \quad \textrm{on $\partial M$}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
Where Latin letters are used to enumerate the spatial components.\\
One can notice that the boundary condition implies constraints on only a part of components of $\psi$. 
For instance, for $\dim M = 3$, we can construct the following generator of Clifford Algebra as suggested in~\cite{Polchinski1998}
\begin{equation*}
\gamma^0 = i\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}  \quad
\gamma^1 = i\begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}  \quad
\gamma^2 = i\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}  
\end{equation*}
Suppose that the normal vector of $\partial M$ is $e_2$ at all point.
We have
\begin{equation*}
1 - i\gamma^\bot = 
\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\ 0 & 0\end{pmatrix} = 2 \mathcal{P}
\end{equation*}
where $\mathcal{P}$ is one of the chiral projectors.
In order to define the domain of the Hamiltonian of the problem, the following lemma is needed 
\begin{lemma}\label{wen-proj}
For $\dim M = 2k+ 3$, $\mathcal{P_\pm} = \frac{1}{2}(1 \pm i\gamma^\bot) $ is a projector and $\rank (\mathcal{P}) = 2^k$
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
It is clear that $(\mathcal{P}_\pm)^{2} = \frac{1}{4}(2\pm 2i \gamma^\bot) = \mathcal{P}_\pm$.
Let us prove the rank by induction over $k$. 
We use the machinery presented in~\cite{Polchinski1998} in order to construct a set of gamma matrices for signature $(-, +, \ldots, +)$ (not the one of our convention). 
To avoid confusion, the gamma matrices denoted by capital Greek letters are taken in this signature, rather than our convention. For $k = 0$ ($\dim M = 3$), we construct the three gamma matrices 
\begin{equation*}
\Gamma^0 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ -1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}  \quad
\Gamma^1 = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix}  \quad
\Gamma^\bot = \Gamma^2 = \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix}  
\end{equation*} 
For a given even-dimensional vector space of dimension $d = 2k + 3$, we can construct a set of gamma matrices $\Gamma^j$ by using the set of gamma matrices $\Sigma^j$ constructed for dimension $2(k-1) + 3$
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
& \Gamma^\mu = \Sigma^\mu \otimes \begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix} \quad 
{\textrm{for }\mu = 0, \ldots, d-4} \\
& \Gamma^{d-3} = \mathbb{1}_{2^k \times 2^k}  \otimes \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 0 \end{pmatrix} \quad \textrm{, }
\Gamma^{d-2} = \mathbb{1}_{2^k \times 2^k} \otimes \begin{pmatrix} 0 & -i \\ i & 0 \end{pmatrix} \quad \textrm{, }
\Gamma^{\bot} = \Gamma^{d-1} = i^{-k}\Gamma^0 \ldots \Gamma^{d-2}
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
It suffices to multiply each gamma matrix by $i$ to go back to our convention. 
Hence, it is equivalent to prove that matrix $\Gamma^\bot$ satisfies $\rank(1 \pm \Gamma^\bot) = 2^k$ in $(2k + 3)$-dimension.
For $k = 0$, the claim obviously holds. 
Suppose that the claim holds for $k - 1$ for a set of gamma matrices $\Sigma^j$. Using the machinery previously presented, we can write $ \Gamma^\bot$ in terms of $\Sigma$
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\Gamma^\bot  & = i^{-k} \Gamma^0 \ldots \Gamma^{d-1} \\
& = i^{-k} \bigg(\Big( \Sigma^0 \ldots \Sigma^{d-3} \Big) \otimes \begin{pmatrix} -1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1\end{pmatrix}\bigg) \times
\bigg(\mathbb{1} \otimes \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & -1 \end{pmatrix} \bigg) \\
& = i^{-k} \Big( \Sigma^0 \ldots \Sigma^{d-3} \Big) \otimes \begin{pmatrix} -i & 0 \\ 0 & -i \end{pmatrix}
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
Therefore
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\rank(1 \pm \Gamma^\bot) & = 
\rank\bigg(1 \pm I^{-(k+1)} \Big(\Sigma^0 \ldots \Sigma^{d-3} \Big) \otimes \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix}\bigg) \\
& = \rank\bigg( \Big(\mathbb{1}_{2^{k} \times 2^{k}}  \mp i^{-(k-1)}\Sigma^0 \ldots \Sigma^{d-3}\Big) \otimes \mathbb{1}_{2 \times 2} \bigg) \\
& = \rank\bigg( 
\underbrace{\Big(\mathbb{1}_{2^{k} \times 2^{k}} \mp \Sigma^\bot \Big)}_{\textrm{of rank $2^{k-1}$ by hypothesis}}
 \otimes \mathbb{1}_{2 \times 2} \bigg)\\
& = 2^k
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
The lemma is thus proven by induction.
\end{proof}
Noticing that the 
As a result, \cref{wen-proj} ensures that the projectors $\mathcal{P}_\pm$ are not identically null and that the projection spaces by both projectors are of equal dimension. 
Thus, one can define an operator $\Delta$ on the     %TODO On what?
\begin{equation}
\Delta = \begin{pmatrix}
i \gamma^0 \gamma^j \partial_j  & 0 \\
c^{-1} \gamma^0 \mathcal{P}_- \cdot \vert_{\partial M}&  i\gamma^0 \gamma^a \partial_a \mathcal{P}_-
\end{pmatrix}
\end{equation}









